cs.CY, cs.HC, cs.CR, cs.SI, cs.CC 

This paper is likely to belong to the sub-category of cs.CY (Computers and Society) as it deals with the policy implications of the GDPR on website design and user consent. It also involves human-computer interaction (HCI) and consumer research, which suggests it could also belong to cs.HC (Human-Computer Interaction). Additionally, the paper discusses the deceptive nature of consent dialogs, which could fall under the sub-category of cs.CR (Cryptography and Security). The study also involves data analysis, which could place it under cs.SI (Social and Information Networks) or cs.CC (Computational Complexity).
